metadata.name: Geo Scribs #19
metadata.description: The aesthetic of projector slides and transparent sheets becharmed my younger studious self. The inaccuracies, finger smudges and colorful markers gave texture and humanness to the coldest mathematical diagrams. The imperfectness of our teachers would be exhibited to us all as the potent light would shine through the tentative circles on those wobbly sheets.

metadata.name: Generative Charts #01 Sushiswap Live Data #32
metadata.description:
Live data charts pulling blockchain data in real time through The Graph decentralized network from Sushiswap subgraph (https://thegraph.com/explorer/subgraph?id=0x4bb4c1b0745ef7b4642feeccd0740dec417ca0a0-0). 

Each chart is uniquely generated. There are 14 possible options of tokens that are visualized, 6 different options of variables (i.e. price USD, liquidity USD, etc..), 7 possible ranges of dates (how many days back), 5 different line types, and a very large number of possible colors. 

Once a chart is generated, it will keep showing live data for its configuration. This does not use a centralized API endpoint, but rather triggers a micro-transaction in GRT to pay for the query to get the latest data (forever covered as part of your mint cost).

metadata.name: Overshoot #18
metadata.description:
Each day at 2 pm, humanity뗩 demand for ecological resources exceeds what earth can regenerate that day. After 2 pm, we live on future generation's expense. This artwork changes to an expressionist version once the overshoot moment has passed, day by day.

This project closes the feedback loop between lifestyle and environmental impact. 10 countries are featured with their individual overshoot moment. In Australia, the resources are completely consumed at 5 am in the morning. In Thailand, the earth뗩 ecological limits are reached at about 4 pm. 

The data is based on the Earth Overshoot Day which is hosted and calculated by Global Footprint Network, an international research organization. Find more here: https://www.overshootday.org/newsroom/country-overshoot-days/ 


Press 딴 to download the SVG file.

metadata.name: Paleterum #14
metadata.description:
Notes: GPU intensive. May not render on some mobile devices. Renders fastest with Chrome.

Controls:
Press 랍 to save .png
Press 1-4 to change resolution:
1 - 1000px * 1410px
2 - 2000px * 2820px 
3 - 3000px * 4230px
4 - 4000px * 5640px 

Default resolution is 1000px * 1410px. It is recommended to explore in 2000px * 2820px or above.

Paleterum (latin 랋late, 락oard)  a flat surface that is used by artists to hold and mix colors.
This artwork is an attempt to simulate the look of watercolor on paper. Inspired by childhood memories that passed through the watercolor sketches of my mother, who was an artist, the piece reflects my admiration for her work and her influence on my own artistic endeavors. 
Intricate forms contrast with the strict forms of cells. All these are echoes from childhood - watercolor lines of a child not bothered by a special artistic idea but trying at least to a fraction of mastering the fine arts and cubes reminiscent of ones which children use to build towers.
Overall, the piece is a tribute to the joy and creativity of childhood, and to the power of artistic inspiration that can be passed down from one generation to the next.

Made with p5js and a few GLSL shaders.
